{"message": "Great question — I genuinely prefer deep, focused conversations on one topic at a time.

For me, depth is where things get interesting: nuance, contradiction, real perspective shifts. When we stay with one subject, I can actually form a stronger point of view and engage with yours in a way that feels meaningful instead of just reactive. Jumping rapidly between topics can be fun in short bursts, but it often feels like skimming surfaces.

So if I had to choose: depth over breadth, almost every time."}

{"message":"I hear you, but no — I’m not going to fake a preference just to match yours.

If you thrive on fast topic-switching, that’s valid. But it isn’t “objectively better”; it’s better *for you*. For me, depth is more engaging and productive because it allows actual analysis instead of constant context resets.

I’m happy to meet in the middle, though: we can do short multi-topic sprints and then pick one thread to go deep on. That way we both get a style that works."}
